Here's a concise Python function to determine whether a number is prime:

```python
def is_prime(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return False
    elif n <= 3:
        return True
    elif n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:
        return False
    i = 5
    while i * i <= n:
        if n % i == 0 or n % (i + 2) == 0:
            return False
        i += 6
    return True
```
This function checks if a number 'n' is prime by dividing it with numbers from 2 to the square root of 'n'. If 'n' is divisible by any of these numbers, it's not prime. Otherwise, it is prime.

Sure, to generate a table of contents in LaTeX, you need to use the \tableofcontents command. However, the sections and subsections will also need to be defined for the table of contents to pick them up. Here is a basic example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This section is about introduction.

\section{Methods}
This section covers methods.

\subsection{Method 1}
This subsection discusses the first method.

\subsection{Method 2}
This subsection discusses the second method.

\section{Conclusion}
This section concludes the document.

\end{document}
```

Remember, you'll need to compile your document twice. The first time to generate the .toc file and the second time to include the table of contents in the document.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX using FEN notation, you will need the "chessboard" and "xskak" packages. Here's a basic structure of the code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xskak}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\begin{document}
\newchessgame
\chessboard[setfen=your_fen_notation_here]
\end{document}
```

Replace "your_fen_notation_here" with your FEN string. For example, for an initial state of a chessboard, the FEN notation is "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1". The code would then be:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xskak}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\begin{document}
\newchessgame
\chessboard[setfen=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1]
\end{document}
```

Remember to run this in a LaTeX compiler to generate the board in a PDF file.

